<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-521-723  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 521 723.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hand-held weather forecasting gadget from Japan. (PilotCorporation of Japan's AMEDEX)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Takahashi, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Pilot Corporation of Japan (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Computer industrySpecial-Purpose ComputersMeteorologyHand-held computersProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>HAND-HELD WEATHER FORECASTING GADGET FROM JAPAN TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 SEP 3 (NB)-- Pilot Corporation of Japan will sell a hand-held weather forecaster calledAMEDEX starting October 1.andP;  The gadget predicts weather by combining pastaccumulated weather data with a current air pressure reading measured by abuilt-in sensor each 30 minutes.andP;  Pilot claims that the devices is 75 percentaccurate in predicting weather which will occur four hours after the readingwithin a radius of 10 kilometers.andP;  The attractive forecaster displays weathersymbols and English-language messages on the LCD (liquid crystal display)screen.andM;Other features include a world clock which simultaneously displays time, day,and principal cities in 24 world zones, a phone directory which can record100 phone numbers, a calculator, and a calendar.andM;AMEDEX measures 185 by 131 by 34 millimeters, and weighs only 310 grams.andM;The price in Japan will be 20,000 yen ($133) and the suggested retail pricein the U.S.andP;  will be $159.95.andP;  Pilot aims to sell 50,000 units in the firstyear.andM;(Ken Takahashi/19900830/Press Contact: Pilot Corporation, 03-5487-8111)</TEXT></DOC>